# **PROG7313\_POE\_PART3**

## **Project Overview**

This is our project for Part 3 of PROG7313. It's a budget tracker Android app. The app saves data online using firebase / firestore  and includes all the required features listed in the project brief.

## **What This Is (Part 3 — App Prototype Development )**

## **Covered Topics**

·        Layouts

·        Event handling

·        Activities and intents

·        firebase (read/write)

## **Features**

·        Login screen with username and password

·        Create categories

·        Add expense entries (date, times, description, category)

·        Optionally add a photo to an expense

·        Set monthly min and max spending goals

·        See a list of expenses between dates

·        Tap entries to view their photo if they have one

·        See totals spent per category in a selected period (search)

Loans feature 

Search feature and graph 

Gamification missions and shop 

·        firebase used for saving everything

·        Inputs are validated, and the app handles errors without crashing

·        GitHub Actions set up for auto builds and checks

## **Stuff We Used**

·        Kotlin

·        Android Studio

·        firebase / firestore

·        GitHub Actions

| gamification | The Gamification features that were implemented into this project revolved into giving the user missions to complete to then get rewarded for doing those missions with coupons and vouchers to help with their budgeting. The virtual currency that is used is called Honey Points, this is the currency that the user will use when navigating the application. The points will be linked to the user's profile and if later into development they want to add another type of currency they will be able to. The Missions Page is what will keep the user coming back to the app and keep the user engaged in the product by trying to keep their budgeting practises on track, and by doing so they will be rewarded with various coupons and vouchers available for the user to purchase with the points that they earned. The missions will be stored on Firestore and will be displayed on a recycler view and by doing these missions over again will reinforce positive behaviours. The reward store is the place where the user will be able to spend the points that they earned on vouchers for useful items that could make a difference in your budgeting. Each reward will have a title, description, and the amount that the item will cost. When the reward is claimed it will be saved to the user’s claimed\_rewards subcollection and this will help the user get the same reward multiple times as if the user only has one store they shop they won’t be forced to go to other ones. The My rewards page is where the user will be able to see their rewards that they have claimed, there will be a title, description and a barcode so that the user will be able to scan it so they can access their voucher. Once the voucher is scanned the user will lose access to that voucher. |

| loans | LoanFragment.kt Yo, this fragment shows all your loans in a list with Edit/Delete buttons and a big “Add Loan” button up top. How it works (loosely): onCreateView → inflate the view, get Firebase uid, hook up the RecyclerView’s layout manager loadLoans() → calls FirestoreManager.getLoans(uid), then sets up the LoanAdapter LoanAdapter → binds loan data (amount, rate, monthly payment, remaining balance) and wires onEdit/onDelete lambdas to reopen the same dialog or delete from the database showLoanDialog() → pops up an a form (amount, rate, months, etc.).after you press save it saves to the database and the calcs the amount left to pay   |
